<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n03102e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03102e">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03102e"> 102(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Cuchulain upper / art of tonsure / 3 parts of body</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> <font color="green">[In this section Columcille is called &lsquo;A Christian Cuchulain&rsquo;]</font> In the Tain we watch the high and vehement Cuchulain accomplishing prodigies of valor &hellip; With his vigorous edge-stroke he could at will take <mark>off all the hair of an opponent from poll to forehead</mark> and from ear to ear as clean as with a razor without drawing blood. With his oblique traverse stroke he could divide an antagonist into <mark>three equal segments</mark> falling simultaneously upon the ground. <small> Benedict Fitzpatrick, <a name="BFIM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BFIM"><cite title="source">Ireland and the Making of Britain</cite></a> (1922) 120</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
